document: {"blocks":[{"key":"a6k34","text":"Introduction","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":12}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"debkh","text":"Fish husbandry and maintenance","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":30}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"45pt4","text":"Adult and juvenile zebrafish of the Tübingen (TU) strain were kept at 28℃ on a 12:12 hour light/dark cycle and housed in either 3.5L or 11L tanks at a maximum density of 5 fish/L. Embryos were kept in egg water (3g/10L, Red Sea “Coral Pro Salt”, RS 11230, Aqua Schwarz) or E2 medium1 at a maximum density of 50 eggs per 30 mL until 5 dpf. Larval fish were kept in egg water at a maximum density of 50 fish per 500mL from 5-14 dpf. Larval/juvenile fish between 5-35 dpf were fed live paramecia once daily. Larval/juvenile fish were fed with brine shrimps (Premium Sander’s Artemia-Eggs, FF 006425, Aqua Schwarz) once per day starting at 14 dpf and in addition flakes (TetraMin Flakes, T 769939, Aqua Schwarz) once per day from 56 dpf. Larvae up to 5 dpf were kept in dishes filled with egg water (60 ug/ml of sea salt in distilled water) or in 0.5X E2 medium (for injected embryos, 7.5 mM NaCl, 0.25 mM KCl, 0.5 mM MgSO4, 75 μM KH2PO4, 25 u μM Na2HPO4, 0.5 mM CaCl2, 0.35 mM NaHCO3, 0.5 mg/L Methylene Blue ) at 28℃ inside an incubator (RuMed 3101, Rubarth Apparate GmbH, Laatzen, Germany) with 12:12 light/dark cycle. All animal procedures were carried out in compliance with the ethical guidelines of the national animal welfare law and approved by the local government.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":282,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fpo00","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"brnli","text":"Procedure","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c0ajb","text":"Generation of transgenic line","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":29}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f8k39","text":"Linearize pT2-2kbStAR:bPAC-2A-tdTomato2(ZFIN ID: ZDB-GENE-001120-3) recombinant plasmids.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":38,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5ugr6","text":"Inject linearized plasmid into 1-cell stage wildtype embryos of TU strain at 10-50 ng/mL in the presence of 10-50 ng/mL Tol2 transpose mRNA and 0.05% phenol red. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8thag","text":"Screen the progenies of injected fish for interrenal gland-specific red fluorescent tdTomato expression to identify founders. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2gv4v","text":"Maintain the established transgenic line, Tg(star:bPAC-2A-tdTomato)uex300+/-by crossing with wild-type TU fish and screening progenies for the presence of interrenal gland-specific red fluorescence (for bPAC+) or absence (for bPAC-) at 4 dpf. In the case of the usage of bPAC+ larvae before 4 dpf, use larvae from Tg(star:bPAC-2A-tdTomato)uex300+/+without screening.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":42,"length":34},{"style":"italic","offset":314,"length":34},{"style":"sup","offset":67,"length":9},{"style":"sup","offset":339,"length":9}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"31tfv","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7mbqk","text":"Sample collection","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":17}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cjklp","text":"Collect all samples within a 2-hour window during the morning (8:30 to 10:30) without feeding. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3qqgf","text":"Immobilize larvae and fish by submersion into ice-cold system water before processing for histology, RNA, or cortisol extraction. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6etmj","text":"For the looming dots (LD)-exposed samples, return subjective fish to a holding tank for 15 minutes after LD exposure before being netted into ice-cold water, to wait for the GC induction.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"650i4","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"iuqq","text":"Whole-body Cortisol assay","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":25}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ab7mv","text":"Place all samples immediately into a tube and then rapidly freeze using dry ice. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a4uk4","text":"A single sample for the larval stage requires 12 larvae whilst from 28 dpf onwards, an individual fish constitutes one sample. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eej3t","text":"Samples can be kept at - 80℃ until further analysis.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d1unp","text":"Thaw the sample at room temperature and add 150 μl or 1 ml/100mg (fish weight) of distilled water to each larval or adult fish sample, respectively. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7em06","text":"For the larval samples, homogenize the sample for 20 seconds using a pestle and micro-tube homogenizer.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cpoqe","text":"For the adult samples, homogenize the sample using KIMBLE Dounce Tissue Grinder (DWK Life Sciences, Mainz, Germany). ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2rap9","text":"Place the homogenized samples on ice and add 1 ml and 8 ml of ethyl acetate (99.5%) to larval or adult samples respectively. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"77tfp","text":"Vortex each sample vigorously for 2 minutes and centrifuge it at 5000 g at 4℃ for 5 minutes or 10 minutes in the case of larval or adult samples, respectively.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7htus","text":"Place the sample on dry ice for 30 seconds to freeze the aqueous layer.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dejnb","text":"Transfer the organic layer (ethyl acetate) to a new tube. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"96ooi","text":"Evaporate the ethyl acetate layer in a vacuum dryer (Concentrator 5301, Eppendorf, Germany) for 30 minutes at 30 ℃. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6osvs","text":"After drying, resuspend the pellet in 20 μl of diluent before measurement. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4vu2l","text":"Perform the competitive cortisol assay (Cisbio HTRF® Cortisol Kit, 62CRTPEG) following the manufacturer’s protocol. ELISA signal can be detected using a CLARIOstar plate reader (BMG Labtech, Ortenberg, Germany).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"57kf8","text":"For each assay, at least 6 samples per group will be required. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1bbvq","text":"The data is presented as cortisol (pg) per larva and cortisol (ng) per weight of fish (g). ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f04f5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7l6lb","text":"Behavior tests for adult fish","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":29}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8hige","text":"Female adult zebrafish (6-9 months old) should be moved into a designated behavior experimental room one week prior to testing and housed in groups of 10 fish in a 3L tank. The behavior experimental room’s water conditions, lighting schedules, and feeding routines should be the same as in the main facility. Experiments should be carried out between 09:00 and 14:00 and fish should not be fed on the morning of testing. Naïve fish should be subjected to multiple experiments on consecutive days. Immediately after testing, fish should be sacrificed for sampling. Fish should not be used in any repeat experiments. For each assay, the water will be changed, and the next experimental fish will be introduced to the tank. We rotated between wild type, bPAC- (where applicable), and bPAC+ fish for each trial.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6seof","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3cabt","text":"Novel tank assay","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":16}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6dmps","text":"The novel tank assay is a trapezoidal tank (25-28 cm (L), 6 cm (W) 9-10 cm (H)) filled with 1.1L of system water. The light intensity should be maintained at 700 LUX at the water’s surface. The tank should be positioned inside a photography dome. The trial will be recorded at 30 FPS using a camera (acA1300-60gm - Basler ace) with an infrared lens. ","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5ukuk","text":"","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"au5rt","text":"Place the tank in front of an infrared back panel to produce contrast. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cam84","text":"Perform live-tracking using Ethovision (EthoVision XT 13, Noldus Information Technology), which generates X and Y coordinates for each frame. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4o674","text":"Net a fish from its home tank into the center of the tank just above the water's surface. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8iol0","text":"Begin the trial as soon as Ethovision detects the fish and continue for five minutes. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9pkta","text":"At the end of the trial, remove the fish and sacrifice it for sampling as described in the sample collection procedure. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7c57e","text":"Calculate behavior parameters using the X and Y coordinates generated by Ethovision and a custom-built python script. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bd4kc","text":"Calculate depth as the average distance from the bottom of the tank in cm for each minute. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bfbc4","text":"Calculate average speed as the average distance moved from the previous frame to the current frame. Then, average for each minute and multiply by 30 to present as cm per second. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"i8bq","text":"Calculate fast swimming as the percentage of frames out of the overall trial that fish spent swimming at over the 12 cm per second threshold.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8i1ak","text":"Calculate immobility as the number of frames spent moving less than 0.1 cm per second for at least 10 consecutive frames, as a percentage of the total trial.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9lceg","text":"","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"csg2l","text":"Social behavior test","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":20}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6t3hi","text":"The social assay is a transparent cuboidal clear acrylic tank (18 cm (L), 11 cm (W) 9 cm (H)) filled with system water (1.2 L). The walls are clear and 1/3rd of the floor is blue, and 2/3rds is white. At the white end is a white opaque divider that blocks the view of the visual stimulus. On the other side of the divider is the social cue tank, a cuboidal clear acrylic tank (13.5 cm (L), 6 cm (W), 9 cm (H)) filled with 0.7 L of system water that is positioned 2 cm from the main tank. Five naïve female wild-type conspecifics should be placed into the social cue tank 30 minutes before testing began to allow for habituation. The tanks should be placed on a platform inside a photography dome. An external light lit up the arena to 550 LUX (3200 Kelvin) at the water surface level.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"frbco","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e10bq","text":"Initiate the trial by netting a fish from the housing tank into the center of the blue and white tank.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fev69","text":"Record fish for 60 seconds with the divider in a closed position, this is called the pre-social phase.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bsip1","text":"After 60 seconds, slide away the divider revealing the social cue. Continue recording for a further 120 seconds, this is referred to as the social phase.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"715qo","text":"Record the trials with two cameras at 30 FPS; a top camera positioned directly above the tank and a side camera positioned in front of the tank together with an infrared back panel to provide contrast.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d33hc","text":"Perform live tracking from both angles using EthoVision. Export and process the X and Y coordinates from each camera in python script to generate 3D coordinates for each frame.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"apgtq","text":"Divide the tank into three zones for analysis, the blue zone, which encompasses the area above the blue floor, the white zone which covers the rest of the tank, and the interaction zone, which is a ‘C’ shaped area within the white zone and will be drawn to encompass the area in which wild-type fish spend 95% of their time in the white zone.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"decep","text":"Calculate the time in each zone during the two stages of the trial using the 3D coordinates as a percentage of the phase. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"57ofa","text":"Calculate the first entry to each zone in seconds from the beginning of the phase. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"jtin","text":"Measure social interactions from the top view coordinates. For this, calculate the swimming direction and turn events whilst the fish are in the interaction zone. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2ioqo","text":"Social interaction refers to an event where a fish swims on the left (L) to the right (R) axis or R to L axis preceded and followed by either entering and leaving the interaction zone or a turn that changes the direction on the axis. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9qajl","text":"Measure immobility as the amount of time a fish spent swimming less than 0.1 cm per second for 10 or more consecutive frames. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d24ns","text":"Measure depth as the average distance from the bottom of the tank in cm.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bthhn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a02aj","text":"Feeding assay","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":13}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8et5r","text":"The feeding tank (16.9 – 18.7 cm (L), 8.7 cm (W), 10 cm (H)) is positioned inside a photography dome and in front of an infrared back panel. A camera is positioned in front of the tank with an infrared filter and recorded the trial at 30 FPS. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cjqev","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5t9h8","text":"Fish should not be fed for 24 hours before testing. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3hob5","text":"Net the Fish from their home tank and place it into the center of the feeding tank. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1u99k","text":"After a 10-minute habituation period, begin recording and live-tracking using Ethovision.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9ntr5","text":"Record following an initial 30 seconds period in which baseline behavior is measured, place 25 pellets (Zebrafeed 200-400, SPAROS) onto the surface of the tank from an Eppendorf tube. The pellets will float and disperse across the surface of the water. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dr8q4","text":"Record the fish for the remaining 9.5 minutes of the trial and count the number of pellets eaten.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"765j5","text":"Manually count each feeding event and define it as a fish eating the pellet when the pellet remains consumed until the end of the trial.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8g0bs","text":"Transfer the X and Y coordinates for each frame into python script and calculate the duration each fish spent in the top 1 cm of the tank (feeding zone) as a percentage of the trial.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2e9a3","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c6ofm","text":"Fear conditioning assay ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":24}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f5eqs","text":"The fear conditioning assay will be performed using the Zantiks AD system (Zantiks, UK)3. The tank will be filled with system water. One fish will be placed into each one of the 4 compartments (20 cm (L), 3.5 cm (W), 15 cm (H)) (2 wildtype fish and 2 bPAC+ fish) that are separated by a white opaque wall. The floor of the tank is transparent and underneath the tank is a display. At each end of the tank are two electric shock plates. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":87,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8blcl","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3ob08","text":"The pre-programmed green aversion script will be immediately started, and the fish will be recorded using the built-in camera. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9pl6u","text":"Following a 30-minute habituation period, the display will show a green background and blue on the other half of the display. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"777qp","text":"For the adaptation phase of the trial, the colors will be flipped every 5 minutes for 30 minutes to measure baseline preference. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dr2se","text":"In the conditioning phase, the screen will display the color blue for 9 seconds and the color green for 1 second. During the 1 second of green, 9 volts will be run through the electric shock plates. This will be repeated 6 times. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"74tvf","text":"After the conditioning phase, in the test phase, the display will be returned to displaying a blue half and a green half. Each variation will be displayed for 1 minute. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"hm0l","text":"The Zantiks system will provide the total amount of time spent in each colored zone for each phase of the trial. For the test phase, the time in the blue zone will be combined with each variation and the average time will be calculated as a percentage. Data from fish that did not move during the test phase will not be included in the analysis.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8u7l1","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bc9v","text":"Locomotion assay","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":16}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"96nns","text":"To measure locomotion, fish will be netted from their home tank into the center of a small tank (16.9 – 18.7 cm (L), 8.7 cm (W), 10 cm (H)) which should be positioned within a photography dome and the light intensity at the water’s surface should be 350 LUX. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"13np1","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fjrp8","text":"Record Fish using a camera positioned in front of the tank using an infrared lens and an infrared panel positioned behind the tank. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"abjli","text":"Perform recording and live-tracking using Ethovision. The fish will be recorded for 3 minutes. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2n1ac","text":"Transfer the X and Y coordinates generated from Ethovision into python script where the average speed and turn frequency will be calculated. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"66avh","text":"Measure average speed as the average distance from the previous frame to the current frame across the trial and present it as cm per second. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"b99e9","text":"Calculate turns as a change of direction event in which the heading angle of the fish changed from left to right or right to left. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"be660","text":"Calculate the average number of turns per second by dividing the total number of turns by 180.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e0m31","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d1lir","text":"Acute stress by a predatory stressor (Looming dots)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":51}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5a8fk","text":"Net a fish into a small tank (16.9 – 18.7 cm (L), 8.7 cm (W), 10 cm (H)) filled with system water and the tank will be immediately placed under a Raspberry Pi display (Raspberry Pi 3 7” display 15.4 cm x 8.6 cm). The Raspberry Pi display runs a Linux operating system which is controlled with a custom-built graphical user interface (GUI) on a master PC. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eegcj","text":"Generate a txt file using the master PC and it will be transferred to the Raspberry PIs via WLAN (PLINK). The file is read by a custom-built script which generates a sequence of images that are presented on the display. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9d65a","text":"After 30 seconds the trial begins. Record the fish at 30 FPS via Ethovision.
